1 and physical materials, that offer detailed information about
2 options for long-term care, tools for planning for long-term care
3 and financial assistance with long-term care that is available to
4 residents of this State.
5 2. In carrying out the provisions of subsection 1, the
6 Department, through the Division, shall:
7 (a) Incorporate best practices from other states and engage a
8 diverse range of stakeholders, including, without limitation,
9 financial planners, providers of health care, insurance companies,
10 senior advocacy groups, nonprofit and grassroots organizations,
11 and local government agencies that work with the elderly
12 population in this State, with an emphasis on engaging with
13 organizations with significant connections to the elderly
14 population in this State and have a thorough understanding of the
15 unique needs and challenges experienced by different segments of
16 the elderly population in this State.
17 (b) Address specific demographic segments within the elderly
18 population in this State, including, without limitation, persons
19 who are not proficient in the English language, veterans and
20 residents of rural communities, to ensure the inclusivity and
21 accessibility of resources.
22 3. The Department, through the Division, may implement the
23 provisions of subsection 1 in phases, with initial priority given to
24 areas of this State with a high concentration of elderly persons
25 and person with limited access to long-term planning resources.
26 The Department may select counties in this State to host pilot
27 programs to test and refine outreach and delivery strategies for
28 implementation statewide.
29 4. The Department, through the Division, shall develop a
30 framework to monitor, evaluate and assess the effectiveness of the
31 program set forth in subsection 1, and to adapt the program as
32 necessary. In monitoring, evaluating, assessing and adapting the
33 program, the Department, through the Division, shall gather input
34 from participants and stakeholders, including, without limitation,
35 nonprofit and grassroots organizations.
36 5. On or before February 1 of each year, the Administrator
37 shall submit a report to the Director of the Legislative Counsel
38 Bureau for transmittal:
39 (a) In even-numbered years, to the Legislative Commission
40 and the Joint Interim Standing Committee on Health and Human
41 Services; and
42 (b) In odd-numbered years, to the next regular session of the
43 Legislature.
44 6. The Division may adopt regulations to carry out the
45 provisions of this section.
